b'This activity seeks to root reforms in the Judiciary with the goal of enhancing access to justice in particular for the most vulnerable and marginalized groups. This will be achieved by strengthening the capacity of the Judiciary to deliver justice in a fair, timely and efficient manner through:-  Provision of technical assistance and capacity building including on ADR and gender justice,  Entrenching use of ICT as an enabler of justice  digitization and use of e-diaries,  Reforming and streamlining laws, policies and procedures that impact the operation of the Judiciary thereby creating technical barriers to justice,  Developing and operationalizing key policies and administrative procedures that facilitate enhanced access to justice,  Strengthening coordination mechanisms of the justice chain through the NCAJ and CuCs, with a special focus on the technical committee on SGBV. It builds upon previous Embassy support to Judiciary Transformation, which was implemented through UNDP (2013 to 2016).'

b'All ten Dutch drinking water companies and their partners (water operators) in developing countries have established a new public private partnership with DGIS. The objective of the partnership is to combine capacity, knowledge, networks and financial means to ensure sustainable access to water for 1 million, mainly urban and poor people. Improving the technical, operational and financial capacity of local water utilities via water operator partnerships (WOPs) is at the heart of the programme. This will be done through peer to peer knowledge exchange and strategic investments. Complementary efforts aim to contribute to improving the enabling policy and regulatory framework for sustainable service delivery. The programmatic approach to this initiative will be utilised to ensure knowledge development and exchange and to facilitate access to additional finance. The implementation of the programme will be gender transformative and will take into consideration the effects of climate change. This programme represents a first of three phases. It is the intention to continue this partnership for the entire SDG period, up to 2030, which will ensure sustainable access to water to 10 million people in total.'

column9: b"This activity is the foliow-up phase of ISA-I that ended in December 2016. ISA-II wiii continue to support the Zambezi Agency (Agency) for inciusive and sustainabie agricuiturai deveiop-ment in the Zambezi Valiey as part of a broader package of development support involving various finandai partners. The Embassy funded ISA-I with EUR 17,49 million. The Mid-term Review (Ecorys, April 2016) concluded that this activity has contributed to the establishment of a solid organisation with a clear vision and mandate and a committed team. The Agency activities facilitated investments that reached 39.986 of farmers and beneficiaries, including poorer ones. The programme is considered very relevant in its basic objective and approach to promote market-oriented agriculture, businesses and value chains. A budget of EUR 73,09 million is secured for the Agency (EUR 61,85 million for ISA-II and EUR 11,24 million from central GoM earmarked for the Agency's running cost). The Embassy will participate with EUR 20 million and the Agency with EUR 30, 59 million. Others such as the World Bank and NICHE cover the remaining EUR 22,50 million of the currently secured amount. The Embassy and the Agency contribution to the programme will reach 43.460 small farmers through the following components: a) Capacity building of the Agency; b) Capacity building directed at educational centres and business development service (BDS) providers; c) Services delivery to small farmers and small businesses."
